## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests, 0 meaningful verifications.** This is a systematic **coverage-touching** suite — every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called exactly once, but almost nothing is asserted. These tests will report ~95% line coverage while catching ~0% of regressions.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| Critical | 7 |
| High | 1 |
| Medium | 2 |
| Low | 0 |

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage-Touching Pattern (systemic — entire class)

All 10 tests follow the same formula: call a method, skip assertions. The naming (`_Works`) and the alphabetical surface-area walk confirm this is coverage-inflation, not verification.

#### 2. No Assertions — 6 tests assert literally nothing

| Test (line) | What it misses |
|---|---|
| `AddProduct_Works` (L17) | Never checks the product is actually stored |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` (L31) | Never checks the price actually changed |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` (L39) | Never checks the product is actually gone |
| `GetProductCount_Works` (L63) | Calls `GetProductCount()`, discards the result |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (L68) | Never checks any price was reduced |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` (L84) | Never checks a product was created |

**Example fix — `AddProduct_Works`:**
```csharp
// BEFORE (L17-21): proves nothing
var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// AFTER: verifies the product was persisted correctly
var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var stored = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(stored);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", stored.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, stored.Price);
```

**Example fix — `UpdatePrice_Works`:**
```csharp
// BEFORE (L31-36): price could stay 9.99 and test still passes
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

// AFTER: verifies the mutation
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

**Example fix — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works`:**
```csharp
// BEFORE (L68-74): 10% discount could be silently broken
